### Next, provide the given income statement.
$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Heir Jordan Corp.}\\
\text{Income Statement}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Sales}&\$49,000.00\\
\text{Cost of Sales}&\underline{40,300.00}\\
\text{Taxable Income}&8,700.00\\
\text{Taxes(22\%)}&\underline{1,914.00}\\
\textbf{Net Income}&\underline{\underline{\$6,786.00}}

\end{array}
$$

### Compute the projected cost of sales.

Using the calculated percentage of the cost of sales, we will use this percentage share to calculate the projected cost of sales.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Cost of Sales}&= \text{Percentage Share of COS} \times \text{Projected Sales}\\[15pt]
&= 82.25\%  \times \$56,350.00\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$46,347.88}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected cost of sales is **$46,347.88**.

###  Compute the business tax.

The business tax is treated as operating cost, which is deducted from the taxable income to compute the net income.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Business Tax}&= \text{Tax Rate} \times \text{Taxable Income}\\[15pt]
&= 22\%  \times \$10,002.12\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$2,200.47}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected business tax is **$2,200.47**.

### Compute the projected dividends.

The projected dividends are computed by multiplying the payout ratio with the net income. The problem assumes that the payout ratio is constant.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Dividends}&= \text{Payout Ratio} \times \text{Net Income}\\[15pt]
&= 35.37\%  \times \$7,801.65\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$2,759.44}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

### Compute the projected cash based on the percentage of increase in sales.

All assets are to be projected in proportion to the increase in sales. The increase in sales is 15%. Therefore to compute the increase in assets, we multiply it by 115%.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Cash}&= \text{Growth in Sales} \times \text{Cash}\\[15pt]
&= 115\%  \times \$2,950.00\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$3,392.50}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected cash is **$3,392.50**.

### Compute the projected accounts receivable based on the percentage of increase in sales.

All assets are to be projected in proportion to the increase in sales. The increase in sales is 15%. Therefore to compute the increase in assets, we multiply it by 115%.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Accounts Receivable}&= \text{Growth in Sales} \times \text{Acct Receivable}\\[15pt]
&= 115\%  \times \$4,100.00\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$4,715.00}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected accounts receivable is **$3,392.50**.

### Compute the projected inventory based on the percentage of increase in sales.

All assets are to be projected in proportion to the increase in sales. The increase in sales is 15%. Therefore to compute the increase in assets, we multiply it by 115%.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Inventory}&= \text{Growth in Sales} \times \text{Inventory}\\[15pt]
&= 115\%  \times \$6,400.00\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$7,360.00}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected inventory is **$7,360.00**.

### Compute the projected plant equipment based on the percentage of increase in sales.

All assets are to be projected in proportion to the increase in sales. The increase in sales is 15%. Therefore to compute the increase in assets, we multiply it by 115%.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Plant Equip't}&= \text{Growth in Sales} \times \text{Plant Equp't}\\[15pt]
&= 115\%  \times \$41,300.00\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$47,495.00}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected plant equipment is **$47,495.00**.

### Compute the projected accounts payable based on the percentage of increase in sales.

Liabilities are not to be projected in proportion to the increase in sales unless otherwise stated. Based on the problem, accounts payable vary with sales. The increase in sales is 15%. Therefore to compute the increase in accounts payable, we multiply it by 115%.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Accts Payable}&= \text{Growth in Sales} \times \text{Accts Payable}\\[15pt]
&= 115\%  \times \$2,400.00\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$2,760.00}} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected accounts payable is **$2,760.00**.

The following assumptions were made regarding the financial plan:
&nbsp;
* Predicted sales growth of 15\%
&nbsp;
* Constant dividend payout ratio
&nbsp;
* Predicted increase in the cost, assets, and accounts payables proportional to sales
&nbsp;
*No new external debt or equity financing

Now, let us compute the increase in the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Increase in Sales}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate of Increase}\\[12pt]
&={\$49,000}\times{15\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$7,350}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The increase in the sales amounts to \$7,350.**

Now, let us compute the projected sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Sales}&=\text{Sales}+\text{Increase in Sales}\\[12pt]
&={\$49,000}+{\$7,350}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$56,350}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected sales is \$56,350.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of cost in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cost}&=\frac{\text{Cost}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$40,300}{\$49,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.82}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{82\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of cost in proportion to the sales is 82\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected cost:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Cost}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$56,350}\times{82\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$46,207}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected cost is \$46,207.**

Now, let us compute the projected taxable income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Taxable Income}&=\text{Projected Sales}-\text{Projected Cost}\\[12pt]
&={\$56,350}-{\$46,207}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$10,143}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Taxable income is \$10,143.**

Now, let us compute the taxes:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Taxes}&=\text{Taxable Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$10,143}\times{22\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,231.46}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected taxes is \$2,231.46.**

Now, let us compute the projected net income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Net Income}&=\text{Taxable Income}-\text{Taxes}\\[12pt]
&={\$10,143}-{\$2,231.46}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$7,911.54}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected net income is \$7,911.54.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of cash in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cash}&=\frac{\text{Cash}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$2,950}{\$49,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.06}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{6\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of cash in proportion to the sales is 6\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Cash:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Cash}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$56,350}\times{6\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$3,381}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Cash is \$3,381.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of accounts receivable in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Accounts Receivable}&=\frac{\text{Accounts Receivable}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$4,100}{\$49,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.08}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{8\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of accounts receivable in proportion to the sales is 8\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Accounts Receivable:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Accounts Receivable}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$56,350}\times{8\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$4,508}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Accounts Receivable is \$4,508.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of Inventory in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Inventory}&=\frac{\text{Inventory}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$6,400}{\$49,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.13}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{13\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of Inventory in proportion to the sales is 13\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Inventory :
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Inventory }&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$56,350}\times{13\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$7,325.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Inventory is \$7,325.50.**

The percentage of sales of total current assets is as follows:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Current Assets}&=\text{Cash}+\text{Accounts Receivable}+\text{Inventory}\\[12pt]
&={6\%+8\%+13\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{27\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of sales of total current assets is 27\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Current Assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Current Assets}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$56,350}\times{27\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$15,214.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Current Assets is \$15,214.50.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of Net Plant and Equipment in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage}&=\frac{\text{ Net Plant and Equipment}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$41,300}{\$49,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.84}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{84\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of Net Plant and Equipment in proportion to the sales is 84\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Net Plant and Equipment:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Net Plant and Equipment}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$56,350}\times{84\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$47,334}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Net Plant and Equipment is \$47,334.**

The percentage of sales of total assets is as follows:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Assets}&=\text{Current Assets}+\text{Fixed Assets}\\[12pt]
&={27\%+84\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{111\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of sales of total assets is 111\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Total Assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Assets}&=\text{Current Assets}+\text{Fixed Assets}\\[12pt]
&={\$15,214.50+\$47,344}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$62,558.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of sales of total assets is \$62,558.50.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of Accounts Payable in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Accounts Payable}&=\frac{\text{Accounts Payable}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$2,400}{\$49,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.05}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{5\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of Accounts Payable in proportion to the sales is 5\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected Accounts Payable:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Accounts Payable}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$56,350}\times{5\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,817.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Accounts Payable is \$2,817.50.**

Now, let us compute the dividend payout ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Dividend Payout Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Dividend}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$2,400}{\$6,786}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.35}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{35\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The dividend payout ratio is 35\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected dividend:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Dividend}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$7,911.54}\times{35\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,769.04}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected dividend is \$2,769.04.**

Now, let us compute the retention ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$4,386}{\$6,786}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.65}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{65\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retention ratio is 65\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$7,911.54}\times{65\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$5,142.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected addition to the retained earnings is \$5,142.50.**

The balance sheet and the corresponding percentage of sales of the accounts are as follows:
&nbsp;
!['slader'](https://slader-solution-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com/f0011356-cab6-4b4e-8a7e-6176730e9f9d-1640663261478780.png)

Now, let us prepare the partial pro forma balance sheet of the company:
&nbsp;
!['slader'](https://slader-solution-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com/cef0c08d-bc01-459f-a201-c3644a00ca87-1640664133067530.png)

Based on the computations, the total current assets increased by  \$1,764.50 while the total current liabilities only increased by  \$417.50. Therefore, the difference could be equal to the short-term notes payable borrowed, leaving the working capital unchanged. The computation for the difference is as follows:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Notes Payable}&=\text{Current Assets}-\text{Current Liabilities}\\[12pt]
&={\$1,764.50}-{\$417.50}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,347}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The borrowed notes payable amounts to \$1,347.**

The projected notes payable is computed as follows:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Notes Payable}&=\text{Notes Payable}+\text{Additional}\\[12pt]
&={\$5,400}+{\$1,347}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$6,747}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected notes payable amounts to \$6,747.**

Now, let us compute the remaining of external financing needed:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{External Financing Needed}&=\text{Balance}-\text{Notes Payable}\\[12pt]
&={\$2,248.50}-{\$1,347}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$901.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The remaining of external financing needed amounts to \$901.50.**

